</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BEF369CE415FFBFF9AB600BFA0B3069" blockId="19.[151,1437,971,1392]" box="[197,1437,1331,1356]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<emphasis id="B924EA8EE415FFBFF9AB600BFE57306E" bold="true" box="[197,449,1331,1356]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">General distribution.</emphasis>
From Massachusetts to North Carolina, west to Texas, Missouri, Illinois, and Michigan.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BEF369CE415FFBFF9AB6060FB25304D" blockId="19.[151,1437,971,1392]" box="[197,1203,1367,1392]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<emphasis id="B924EA8EE415FFBFF9AB6060FEF63052" bold="true" box="[197,352,1368,1392]" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Larval hosts.</emphasis>
White oak (
<taxonomicName id="4C504D1FE415FFBFF8826060FD143052" box="[492,642,1368,1392]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fagaceae" genus="Quercus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fagales" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="alba">
<emphasis id="B924EA8EE415FFBFF8826060FD143052" box="[492,642,1368,1392]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Quercus alba</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
L.) and northern red oak (
<taxonomicName id="4C504D1FE415FFBFFAC46060FB9B3052" box="[938,1037,1368,1392]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fagaceae" genus="Quercus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fagales" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="rubra">
<emphasis id="B924EA8EE415FFBFFAC46060FB9B3052" box="[938,1037,1368,1392]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Q. rubra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
L., 
<taxonomicName id="4C504D1FE415FFBFFD57606FFB31304D" box="[1081,1191,1367,1391]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fagaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fagales" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Fagaceae</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
